The paper discusses the development of intelligent agents to play the game Angry Birds, which involves physics-based simulation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also presents proofs for the computational complexity of the game, which involves decision problems and reductions from other known problems, indicating that it may also belong to the sub-category of Computational Complexity (cs.CC). The use of game engine dynamics to model the physics simulator as an opponent suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Game Theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves the analysis of the game's environment and mechanics, which may suggest that it belongs to the sub-category of Control Systems (cs.SY) or Computer Graphics (cs.CG).
